description: From Middle English befilen, from Old English befȳlan (“to befoul, defile, make dirty”), from Proto-West Germanic *bi- (“be-”) + *fūlijan (“to make foul”), equivalent to be- +‎ file. Cognate with Scots befile (“to befile”), Dutch bevuilen (“to soil, dirty”). See also defile.

verbs.description: befile (third-person singular simple present befiles, present participle befiling, simple past and past participle befiled)

entries.meaning: (transitive, dialectal or obsolete) To make filthy; befoul; soil.
